<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="MER01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Robert</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Merry</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1755-04"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1798-12-24"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">poet</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Merry was a poet and dramatist with radical tendencies. In August 1791, he married the actress Ann Brunton who had appeared in his 1791 tragedy <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Lorenzo</title> 
    and when she was offered an engagement in New York, they emigrated there in 1796.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">It is interesting that Godwin enters Merry under 1793 in the 1796 list of first meetings. This
      implies that the two previous appearances of Merry did not involve Godwin meeting him:</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">14 July 1791: 'Crown &amp; Anchor: <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="ROU01">Rous</persName> &amp; Merry: <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HOL02">B. Hollis</persName>, 
        Shore, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="BAR07">Barbauld</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="DIS01">Disney</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="JEN01">Jennings</persName>, 
      <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="REE01">Rees</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="MOR99">Morgan</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="LIN01">Lindsey</persName>, 
        <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="LEW02">Lewis</persName>.'</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">28 May 1792: 'Holcroft dines with Merry &amp; <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="PAI01">Pain{e}</persName>.'</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The second clearly makes sense - Godwin is enviously recording <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="HOL01">Holcroft's</persName> dinner. Regarding the earlier entry:
      'On 14 July 1791, the second anniversary of the fall of the Bastile, Godwin and nine hundred others
      again assembled for a celebratory dinner at the Crown and Anchor in the Strand. Robert Merry, the
      Della Cruscan poet, had composed an Ode with a bold metaphor drawn from <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="PRI01">Priestley's</persName> scientific
      discoveries which was set to music and sung.' (St Clair, p. 51). Godwin records Merry, which probably refers to his presence and his Ode, but the 1796 list 
      suggests that he did not consider that he had met him that night.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">There is one mention of Merry in 1799, the year after his death, as a topic for a conversation, but the Merry mentioned in 
  1814 is uncoded. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Godwin records his death</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="other"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title></bibl><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="printedbook">William St Clair, <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">The Godwins and the Shelleys</title></bibl><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="appearancesInDiary"><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1788"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1789"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1790"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1791"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1791-07-14" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1792"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1792-05-28" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1793"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1793-07-05" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1793-08-11" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1794"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-06-11" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-06-11" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-06-15" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-06-28" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-06-30" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-07-01" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-07-02" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-07-05" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-07-13" n="notVenue" type="ah"/><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1794-07-15" n="venue" type="nah"/><date xmlns="http://w